WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.000
Hey there, future web developers.

00:00:03.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Did you know JavaScript has several ways to display data?

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:09.000
Whether you're updating a web page or testing code,

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:11.000
JavaScript's got you covered.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Let's break it down into four simple methods.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:17.000
Quick and easy, just like we like it.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:21.000
First up, using innerHTML.

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:23.000
This is like filling in a shape or form.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:26.000
JavaScript finds an existing element by its ID

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:28.000
and updates the content.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:31.000
Here's how it works.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.000
This code grabs the p-tag with the ID demo

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:36.000
and changes its content to...

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.000
you guessed it.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:39.000
Hello world!

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:43.000
Super handy for updating content dynamically.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:46.000
Next we have document write.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:48.000
It's like the loudspeaker of JavaScript.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:53.000
It outputs directly into the HTML document.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:55.000
But watch out.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:58.000
If you use document write after the page has loaded,

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:00.000
it wipes out everything on your page.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:03.000
See this example.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:06.000
Here we run the code when the user clicks the button.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:09.000
So, after the page has finished loading.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:13.000
Oops, it replaces our entire page.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:16.000
So great for quick testing, but not for production.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:18.000
Want to grab someone's attention?

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:21.000
Use an alert box with window alert,

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:26.000
or just alert since the window part is optional.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:29.000
This pops up a box with the result.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.000
Great for quick notifications, but don't overuse it,

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.000
unless you like annoying your users.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.000
And finally, the secret weapon for debugging.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:41.000
Console. Log.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:43.000
Think of it like a journal for your code.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.000
It logs messages straight to the browser console.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:50.000
Use this to test your code behind the scenes

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:52.000
and to test the user experience.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.000
It's a developer's best friend.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:57.000
When testing console methods,

00:01:57.000 --> 00:01:59.000
you need to have the console view visible.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:04.000
This is usually opened by pressing F12.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:06.000
One last trick.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:09.000
While JavaScript doesn't have a direct send to printer function,

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:13.000
you can use window print to print the current page.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:16.000
Easy peasy. Just one button click and voila.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:19.000
Old timey paper printed content.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:21.000
So there you have it.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:23.000
Four ways to display data in JavaScript

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:25.000
plus a bonus printing tip.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:29.000
Try them out and see which one works best for your projects.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:31.000
Thanks for watching.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:34.000
